3. Of course it is very natural that the language of common practical life, such as is employed in the Old and in the N ew Testa- ment, should not be furnished with words which distinguish the facul- ties, powers, and habits of man, in such a manner as to conform with the systems of philosophers, even when these are quite reasonable and true. The analysis and the method which are necessary in phi- Iosophy, are not needed for the purposes of Scripture.

As our author says, the Hebrew, in order to denote the Conscience‚ speaks either of the Heart or of the Spirit of man: and, in like manner, the New Testament uses the Spirit of a Man for his Conscience. 1 Gor. ii. 11.

But such terms as Heart, Mind, Soul, Spirit, in Scripture, though used with discrimination, are not appropriated with metaphysical ex- actness to distinct faculties and powers in man.

Taylor (Chap. 1. Art. 8) gives the same Hebrew words with the same interpretation, and the quotations, Eccles. vii. 22, Prov. xviii. 14, 1 John iii. 21.
